          "id": 4537,
          "question": "How does COVID-19 spread?",
          "answer": "\n\nThe virus is thought to spread mainly from person-to-person, by respiratory droplets released when an infected person talks, coughs, or sneezes. Another person can become infected if the droplets land in their mouth or nose and possibly if the droplets are inhaled into the lungs. The virus might also spread to a person’s hands from a contaminated surface and then to their nose, mouth, or possibly their eyes. Not everyone infected with the virus has symptoms.\n\nThere is [growing scientific evidence](https://academic.oup.com/cid/article/doi/10.1093/cid/ciaa939/5867798) that smaller particles of the COVID-19 virus in the air indoors can infect people. These lighter, finer droplets — that we all exhale from coughing or talking — may stay in the air for several hours, especially when there’s poor ventilation or overcrowding. \n\nYou could become infected if you have indoor contact with those aerosols for an extended period of time.\n\nFollow these general precautions to help prevent the virus from spreading:\n\n*   Wear a [cloth face mask or covering](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19-VDH-mask-guidance.pdf)\n*   Keep a 6-foot distance from others\n*   Wash your hands often\n*   Stay home if you are sick.\n\nLearn more from the CDC about [how to protect yourself and others from getting sick](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/prevention.html).",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
