          "id": 4541,
          "question": "Can pets get sick from COVID-19? What should I do if I own a pet?",
          "answer": "\n\nWe are still learning about the virus that causes COVID-19, but it appears that it can spread from people to animals in some situations. \n\nThere have been a few confirmed cases of animals infected with COVID-19:\n\n*   a [tiger at a zoo in New York](http://www.aphis.usda.gov/aphis/newsroom/news/sa_by_date/sa-2020/ny-zoo-covid-19)\n*   two [pet cats in New York](https://www.cdc.gov/media/releases/2020/s0422-covid-19-cats-NYC.html)\n*   a [cat in Minnesota](https://content.govdelivery.com/accounts/MNBAH/bulletins/28eac81) \n*   a [dog in New York](https://www.aphis.usda.gov/aphis/newsroom/stakeholder-info/sa_by_date/sa-2020/sa-06/sars-cov-2-dog)\n\nThe CDC recommends the following: \n\nUntil we learn more about how this virus affects animals, treat pets as you would other human family members to protect them from a possible infection.\n\nBecause there is a small risk that people with COVID-19 could spread the virus to animals, CDC recommends that pet owners limit their pet’s interaction with people outside their household.\n\n*   Keep cats indoors when possible and do not let them roam freely outside.\n*   Walk dogs on a leash at least 6 feet away from others.\n*   Avoid public places where large numbers of people gather.\n*   Do not put face coverings on pets. Covering a pet’s face could harm them.\n\nTalk to your veterinarian if your pet gets sick or if you have any concerns about your pet’s health.\n\nLearn more about what to do [if you have pets](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/daily-life-coping/pets.html) and answers to [frequently asked questions about COVID-19 and animals](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/faq.html#COVID-19-and-Animals) from the CDC.\n\nRead the [COVID-19 FAQs for pet owners](https://www.avma.org/resources-tools/animal-health-and-welfare/covid-19/covid-19-faqs-pet-owners) from the American Veterinary Medical Association.",
