          "id": 4547,
          "question": "How long is the turnaround for testing?",
          "answer": "\n\nTest results will be available typically within 1 to 3 days. You will get your test results from your health care provider. However, if you received a positive result, the Health Department will also reach out to talk to you about public health recommendations and ask questions about people you were in contact with. It is possible that the Health Department may contact you before your health care provider does.\n\nIf you got tested at a pop-up testing site, you will get a call from the Health Department when your results are ready, which is usually within 2 to 4 days, if not sooner. You will also get a letter in the mail within 7 days of being tested.\n\nFind out [what to do while you're waiting for test results](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/HS-ID-COVID19-Waiting-For-Test-Results-Handout.pdf). Contact your health care provider with any questions.\n\nThe number of Vermonters who were tested for COVID-19 is updated daily on the [Current Activity in Vermont data dashboard](https://www.healthvermont.gov/COVID19-currentactivity).",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        },
        {
          "id": 4547,
          "question": "When will I receive my test results?",
          "answer": "\n\nTest results will be available typically within 1 to 3 days.\n\nHow you receive results varies depending on where you were tested.\n\nIf you were tested at a Health Department popup testing site (for people without symptoms), you will get a call from the Health Department when your results are ready, which is usually within 2 to 4 days, if not sooner. You will also get a letter in the mail within 7 days of being tested. Health Department tests sites are listed [here](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/testing-covid-19#popup).\n\nIf you got tested anywhere else, the Health Department cannot provide your results. Please contact your health care provider if they ordered the test, or the facility that conducted the test.\n\nIf you received a positive result, the Health Department will also reach out to talk to you about public health recommendations and ask questions about people you were in contact with. It is possible that the Health Department may contact you before your health care provider does.",
          "date": "2020-07-24"
        }
      ]
    },
