    {
      "id": 4559,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4559,
          "question": "Are there any recommendations for older adults and people of any age with underlying medical conditions?",
          "answer": "\n\nAccording to the CDC, risk for severe illness from COVID-19 increases with age, with [older adults](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/need-extra-precautions/older-adults.html) at highest risk. People of any age with [certain underlying medical conditions](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/need-extra-precautions/people-with-medical-conditions.html?CDC_AA_refVal=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.cdc.gov%2Fcoronavirus%2F2019-ncov%2Fneed-extra-precautions%2Fgroups-at-higher-risk.html) are also at increased risk for severe illness. In addition to the general [COVID-19 prevention](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/about-coronavirus-disease-covid-19) steps, these groups should consider limiting their risk:\n\n*   Stay close to home as much as possible. Traveling out of state is not recommended since the virus is still widespread in neighboring states and across the country.\n*   Be aware of your surroundings. Choose outdoor settings over indoor settings. Pay attention to the size of the space, crowding, the number of people there, and if they are wearing face coverings and keeping a 6-foot distance.\n*   Choose activities that don’t require close contact. Minimize close contact while talking or doing anything that requires exertion, shouting or singing.\n*   Keep your social circle small. Choose a few other trusted households that are also taking health and safety precautions.\n\nThe CDC recommends [other populations](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/need-extra-precautions/other-at-risk-populations.html) also take extra precautions, like pregnant people, people experiencing homelessness, and people with disabilities.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 4560,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4560,
          "question": "What do I do if I believe I had close contact with someone who has COVID-19?",
          "answer": "\n\nIf you have been in close contact with a person who tested positive for COVID-19, monitor yourself for symptoms. This includes checking your temperature every day, watching for [symptoms](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/about-coronavirus-disease-covid-19) and staying home. [Sign up with Sara Alert](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/EpiInfoWebSurvey/Home/9c2e5941-1ba7-4ab4-84be-558ba7684f5d) – a free, automated and secure reminder system to check for common symptoms of COVID-19.\n\nIf you develop symptoms of COVID-19 and are a close contact of someone who tested positive, you should:\n\n1.  Call your health care provider and\n2.  Call the Vermont Department of Health at 802-863-7240.\n\nIf you do not develop symptoms, you do not need to call the Health Department.\n\nFind out [what to do if you're a close contact of someone with COVID-19](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19_What-to-do-if-you-are-a-close-contact-of-someone-with-COVID-19_final.pdf).",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        },
        {
          "id": 4560,
          "question": "What do I do if I think I had close contact with someone who has COVID-19?",
          "answer": "\n\nIf someone tests positive for COVID-19, they are contacted by the Health Department. They are asked questions about their activities within a certain timeframe – to help identify anyone they had close contact with. (Close contact means being closer than 6 feet apart for a long time while the person was infectious.) This is called contact tracing. \n\nIf the Health Department determines that you were a close contact of the person who tested positive, then the Health Department will call you to tell you [what you need to do](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19_What-to-do-if-you-are-a-close-contact-of-someone-with-COVID-19_final.pdf). \n\nIf the Health Department determines you are **not** a close contact, then you will not be called. You can continue to take the general precautions to slow the spread of the virus: wear a [face mask or covering](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19-VDH-mask-guidance.pdf), keep a 6-foot distance from others you do not live with, wash your hands often, and stay home if you are sick.",
          "date": "2020-07-29"
        },
        {
          "id": 4560,
          "question": "What do I do if I think I had close contact with someone who has COVID-19?",
          "answer": "\n\nIf someone tests positive for COVID-19, they are contacted by the Health Department. They are asked questions about their activities within a certain timeframe – to help identify anyone they had close contact with. (Close contact means being closer than 6 feet apart for a long time while the person was infectious. Other factors, such as the nature of the contact with the person, can influence who is determined a close contact.) This is called contact tracing.\n\nIf the Health Department determines that you were a close contact of the person who tested positive, then the Health Department will call you to tell you [what you need to do](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19_What-to-do-if-you-are-a-close-contact-of-someone-with-COVID-19_final.pdf).\n\nIf the Health Department determines you are **not** a close contact, then you will not be called. While contact tracers work to identify all close contacts, all might not be identified. If you think that you might be a close contact but didn't get a call from the Health Department, you may take precautions by quarantining for 14 days since the last day you were in contact with that person, and get tested on day 7 or after if you have not had any symptoms.\n\nIf you are not a close contact of a person who tested positive, you can continue to take the general precautions to slow the spread of the virus: wear a [face mask or covering](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19-VDH-mask-guidance.pdf), keep a 6-foot distance from others you do not live with, wash your hands often, and stay home if you are sick.",
          "date": "2020-07-31"
        }
      ]
    },
