    },
    {
      "id": 4567,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4567,
          "question": "Is it okay to travel within the United States? Do I need to quarantine when I return?",
          "answer": "\n\nCOVID-19 cases and deaths have been reported in all 50 states, and the situation is constantly changing. Travel increases your chances of getting and spreading COVID-19. According to the CDC, staying home is the best way to protect yourself and others from getting sick. Don’t travel if you are sick or travel with someone who is sick.\n\nRead the CDC’s [considerations for travelers](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/travel-in-the-us.html) if you are thinking of traveling away from your local community.\n\nCheck the Health Department’s webpage for [what to do when you return to Vermont](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/traveling-vermont). Get the latest travel and quarantine guidance, sign up to get daily symptom check reminders by email, text or phone, learn about testing options during quarantine, and find out how to safely connect with friends and family.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        },
        {
          "id": 4567,
          "question": "Is it okay to travel within the United States? Do I need to quarantine when I return?",
          "answer": "\n\nCOVID-19 cases and deaths have been reported in all 50 states, and the situation is constantly changing. Travel increases your chances of getting and spreading COVID-19. According to the CDC, staying home is the best way to protect yourself and others from getting sick. Don’t travel if you are sick or travel with someone who is sick. Read the CDC’s [considerations for travelers](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/travel-in-the-us.html) if you are thinking of traveling away from your local community.\n\nVermonters may travel to [certain counties with low rates of active cases](https://accd.vermont.gov/covid-19/restart/cross-state-travel). If you make your trip in a personal vehicle, you do not need to quarantine upon return to Vermont. If you travel out of state to a location other than those counties with low rates of active cases, you must quarantine in Vermont for 14 days upon return. This includes day trips.\n\nAnyone currently under quarantine who has had no symptoms during the first seven days of quarantine has the option to be tested with a PCR test. Find out how under “[I am under a 14-day quarantine. Can I have the option to be tested and end my quarantine period?](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/COVID/faq/#4692)” on this page.\n\nCheck the Health Department’s webpage for [what to do when you return to Vermont](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/traveling-vermont). Get the latest travel and quarantine guidance, sign up to get daily symptom check reminders by email, text or phone, learn about testing options during quarantine, and find out how to safely connect with friends and family.",
          "date": "2020-07-24"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 4568,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4568,
          "question": "Do family members of people who traveled internationally or by cruise ship need to stay at home?",
          "answer": "\n\nIf your family member has traveled internationally to any country or traveled by cruise ship or river cruise voyage, they should quarantine for 14 days, and the other household members should do self-observation for 14 days.\n\nCheck the Health Department’s webpage for [what to do if you are visiting or returning to Vermont](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/traveling-vermont). Get the latest travel and quarantine guidance, sign up to get daily symptom check reminders by email, text or phone, learn about testing options during quarantine, and find out how to safely connect with friends and family.\n\nFind more information from the CDC about [returning from international travel](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/after-travel-precautions.html) and [returning from cruise ship and river cruise voyages](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/returning-cruise-voyages.html).\n\nStay up to date on the [latest COVID-19 travel advisories from the CDC](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/).",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        },
        {
          "id": 4568,
          "question": "I traveled internationally or by cruise ship. Do I need to quarantine?",
          "answer": "\n\nIf you’ve returned from international travel or from a cruise ship or river cruise voyage, you must quarantine for 14 days. Other members of your household who did not travel do not need to quarantine, but should observe themselves symptoms for 14 days. Learn about [isolation, quarantine and self-observation](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19-chart-observation-isolation-quarantine_final.pdf).\n\nIf you or your household members develop [symptoms of COVID-19](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/about-coronavirus-disease-covid-19), contact your health care provider right away. If you do not have a health care provider, call 2-1-1 to be connected with a local [community or hospital-connected clinic](https://www.navigateresources.net/211vermont/Subcategory.aspx?;;0;;N;0;276976;Health%20Care,%20Dental%20Care).\n\nCheck the Health Department’s webpage for [what to do if you are visiting or returning to Vermont](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/traveling-vermont). Get the latest travel and quarantine guidance, sign up to get daily symptom check reminders by email, text or phone, learn about testing options during quarantine, and find out how to safely connect with friends and family.\n\nFind more information from the CDC about [returning from international travel](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/after-travel-precautions.html) and [returning from cruise ship and river cruise voyages](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/returning-cruise-voyages.html).\n\nStay up to date on the [latest COVID-19 travel advisories from the CDC](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/).",
          "date": "2020-07-24"
        },
        {
          "id": 4568,
          "question": "I traveled internationally or by cruise ship. Do I or my household members need to quarantine?",
          "answer": "\n\nIf you’ve returned from international travel or from a cruise ship or river cruise voyage, you must quarantine for 14 days. Other members of your household who did not travel do not need to quarantine, but should observe themselves for symptoms for 14 days. Learn about [isolation, quarantine and self-observation](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19-chart-observation-isolation-quarantine_final.pdf).\n\nIf you or your household members develop [symptoms of COVID-19](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/about-coronavirus-disease-covid-19), contact your health care provider right away. If you do not have a health care provider, call 2-1-1 to be connected with a local [community or hospital-connected clinic](https://www.navigateresources.net/211vermont/Subcategory.aspx?;;0;;N;0;276976;Health%20Care,%20Dental%20Care).\n\nCheck the Health Department’s webpage for [what to do if you are visiting or returning to Vermont](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/traveling-vermont). Get the latest travel and quarantine guidance, sign up to get daily symptom check reminders by email, text or phone, learn about testing options during quarantine, and find out how to safely connect with friends and family.\n\nFind more information from the CDC about [returning from international travel](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/after-travel-precautions.html) and [returning from cruise ship and river cruise voyages](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/returning-cruise-voyages.html).\n\nStay up to date on the [latest COVID-19 travel advisories from the CDC](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/).",
