      "id": 4572,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4572,
          "question": "How long can the virus live on surfaces?",
          "answer": "\n\nCurrent evidence suggests that the COVID-19 virus may live for hours to days on surfaces made from a variety of materials, according to the CDC. It may be possible that a person can get COVID-19 by touching a surface or an object that has the virus on it and then touching their own mouth, nose, or possibly their eyes. However, this is not thought to be the main way the virus spreads. The virus is thought to spread mainly from person-to-person.\n\nCleaning and disinfecting frequently touched surfaces daily are the best ways to help stop the spread of the COVID-19 virus in households and community settings.\n\nFollow the steps for [how to clean and disinfect your home](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/disinfecting-your-home.html) from the CDC.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 4573,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4573,
          "question": "What if I’ve had contact with someone who is under monitoring?",
          "answer": "\n\nIf you have been in a home or in close contact with a person who is under monitoring, you do not need to take any additional steps — as long as you are not experiencing COVID-19 symptoms.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 4575,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4575,
          "question": "What does close contact mean?",
          "answer": "\n\nClose contact means being within 6 feet, for a long time, of someone who has tested positive for COVID-19 during their infectious period, which starts two days (48 hours) before any symptoms began, or for people who didn't have symptoms, two days before they got tested, and continues until they are recovered. Close contact does not mean being more than 6 feet away in the same indoor environment for a long period of time, walking by, or briefly being in the same room with someone.\n\nA “long period of time” is hard to define because it depends on whether the person was sick at the time and what type of interaction you had with that person. These examples can help you determine whether you were a close contact or not.\n\n**Examples of close contacts:**\n\n*   You live in the same home.\n*   You are intimate partners.\n*   You rode in the same car while the person was infectious.\n*   You had dinner together while the person was infectious.\n\n**Examples of** _**not**_ **close contacts:**\n\n*   You were their cashier at the grocery store.\n*   You were their server at a restaurant.\n*   You are a pharmacist who gave the person medication.\n*   You were in front of the person in line at the store.\n*   You are a coworker who briefly walked by to ask a question.\n\nA team at the Health Department works with people with COVID-19 to identify their close contacts. This is called contact tracing. The team assesses each close contact for their exposure risk and gives them health guidance and recommendations for self-isolation or other restrictions.\n\nAs the state reopens, Vermonters should consider keeping a contact journal – a list of other people who you have been in close contact with\neach day. If you do get sick, this would make it easier to get in touch\nwith those people and so they can take proper precautions to prevent further spread of COVID-19.\n\nThe chart describing [what is isolation, quarantine and self-observation](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19-chart-observation-isolation-quarantine_final.pdf) has details about what you should do and not do, depending on your exposure risk.\n\nFind out more about [what to do if you are a close contact of someone who is diagnosed with COVID-19](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19_What-to-do-if-you-are-a-close-contact-of-someone-with-COVID-19_final.pdf).",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        },
        {
          "id": 4575,
          "question": "What does close contact mean?",
          "answer": "\n\nClose contact means being within 6 feet, for a long time, of someone who has tested positive for COVID-19 during their infectious period, which starts two days (48 hours) before any symptoms began, or for people who didn't have symptoms, two days before they got tested, and continues until they are recovered. Close contact does not mean being more than 6 feet away in the same indoor environment for a long period of time, walking by, or briefly being in the same room with someone.\n\nA “long period of time” is hard to define because it depends on whether the person was sick at the time and what type of interaction you had with that person. Here are some examples:\n\n**Examples of close contacts:**\n\n*   You live in the same home.\n*   You are intimate partners.\n*   You rode in the same car while the person was infectious.\n*   You had dinner together while the person was infectious.\n\n**Examples of** _**not**_ **close contacts:**\n\n*   You were their cashier at the grocery store.\n*   You were their server at a restaurant.\n*   You are a pharmacist who gave the person medication.\n*   You were in front of the person in line at the store.\n*   You are a coworker who briefly walked by to ask a question.\n\nA team at the Health Department works with people with COVID-19 to identify their close contacts. This is called contact tracing. If the Health Department determines that you were a close contact of the person who tested positive, then the Health Department will call you to tell you [what you need to do](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19_What-to-do-if-you-are-a-close-contact-of-someone-with-COVID-19_final.pdf).\n\nAs the state reopens, Vermonters should consider keeping a contact journal – a list of other people who you have been in close contact with\neach day. If you do get sick, this would make it easier to get in touch\nwith those people and so they can take proper precautions to prevent further spread of COVID-19.",
          "date": "2020-07-29"
        }
