      "id": 4576,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4576,
          "question": "Can the COVID-19 virus spread through pools and hot tubs?",
          "answer": "\n\nThere is no evidence that the virus can spread to people through the use of pools, hot tubs or water playgrounds. Proper operation and disinfection of the water (for example, with chlorine and bromine) should kill the virus.\n\nEveryone should follow these general precautions to help prevent the COVID-19 virus from spreading: wear a cloth face mask or covering when you’re not in the water, keep a 6-foot distance from others, wash your hands often, and stay home if you are sick.\n\nFind more more frequently asked questions about [COVID-19 and water](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/faq.html?CDC_AA_refVal=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.cdc.gov%2Fcoronavirus%2F2019-ncov%2Fphp%2Fwater.html#Water) from the CDC.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 4577,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4577,
          "question": "What does social distancing mean?",
          "answer": "\n\nSocial distancing means maintaining a physical distance (approximately 6 feet or 2 meters) from people you do not live with. This includes when you’re inside a store, gathering with friends or family, or outside for exercise or a walk.\n\nThe COVID-19 virus spreads easily from person-to-person. It travels through the air from respiratory droplets released when an infected person coughs, sneezes or talks. A person can be infected and not have any symptoms. In addition to keeping a 6-foot distance from others, everyone should:\n\n*   Stay home to protect others if you are sick.\n*   Wear a [cloth face mask or covering](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19-VDH-mask-guidance.pdf) in public settings when you cannot keep a 6-foot distance from other people, for example, at the grocery store or on a crowded sidewalk or bike path.\n*   Wash your hands often with soap and water for at least 20 seconds, especially after being in a public place, going to the bathroom, before eating, and after blowing your nose, coughing, or sneezing.\n*   Keep groups small when you can to limit any possible exposure, and follow health and safety precautions. Learn how to [safely connect with friends and family](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/Safely_Connect_with_Friends_and_Family_FINAL.pdf).",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 4578,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4578,
          "question": "How is a sample collected for COVID-19 testing?",
          "answer": "\n\nUsually a health care provider collects samples (specimens) from you in one of two ways, but there are other options:\n\n1.  The health care provider collects a sample using a nasopharyngeal or NP swab. This is when a long, dry swab is inserted through one nostril and is rubbed against the back of your nose and throat.\n2.  The health care provider collects a sample using a nasal swab. This is when a short, dry swab is used to collect a sample from the front of your nose.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
