    {
      "id": 4583,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4583,
          "question": "I’m young. Can I continue to socialize?",
          "answer": "\n\nWhatever your age, staying home is still the best way to lower our risk of COVID-19, but many of us are eager to take small steps to safely see our friends and family again. Learn how to [safely connect with friends and family](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/Safely_Connect_with_Friends_and_Family_FINAL.pdf).\n\nEven though the risk for severe illness increases with age and is higher for older adults and people of any age with certain underlying medical conditions, young people can also get sick. The virus can spread even if a person does not have any symptoms. Taking health and safety precautions protects everyone and helps slow the spread of this virus. Everyone should wear a [cloth face mask or covering](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19-VDH-mask-guidance.pdf), keep a 6-foot distance from others, wash your hands often, and stay home if you are sick.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 4584,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4584,
          "question": "How should we practice social distancing with children?",
          "answer": "\n\nSocial distancing means keeping at least 6 feet away from others and avoiding places where you may be close to other people. \n\nChoose other trusted households to socialize with that are also taking health and safety precautions, such as family, neighbors or friends. A trusted household is one that has taken seriously the importance of social distancing and proper hygiene in their day-to-day lives. Learn how to [safely connect with friends and family](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/Safely_Connect_with_Friends_and_Family_FINAL.pdf). \n\nChoose outdoor activities where it’s easy to maintain a 6-foot distance. Remember that ticks are active this time of year. Learn how to [Be Tick Smart and prevent tick bites](http://www.healthvermont.gov/BeTickSmart).\n\nContinue to take advantage of technology to play games or keep in touch with friends and family who you are not meeting up with in person. These changes will continue to be difficult, but we are all doing our part to slow down this pandemic.\n\nMost people who get sick from COVID-19 – including children – will experience mild symptoms and recover, but following the general precautions of [wearing a cloth face mask or covering](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID19-childfacecovering.pdf), keeping a 6-foot distance from others, washing hands often, and staying home if you are sick will help us limit the virus’s spread to our vulnerable populations.\n\nFind more [resources for families with children](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/resources).",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        },
        {
          "id": 4584,
          "question": "How can children socialize while still preventing the spread of COVID-19?",
          "answer": "\n\nWhen children are socializing, it’s best for them to keep at least 6 feet away from people they do not live with and to avoid places where they may be close to other people. It’s also important for parents – and children over 2 who are able – to wear cloth face masks or coverings when you’re around people you do not live with. Learn more about [face coverings for children](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID19-childfacecovering.pdf).\n\nIf you choose to socialize with family, friends and neighbors, choose other trusted households that are also taking health and safety precautions and keep groups small whenever possible. A trusted household is one that has taken seriously the importance following these general precautions in their day-to-day lives: wearing cloth face masks or coverings, keeping a 6-foot distance from others, washing their hands often, and staying home if they are sick.\n\nChoose outdoor activities where it’s easy to maintain a 6-foot distance. Remember that ticks are active this time of year. Learn how to [Be Tick Smart and prevent tick bites](http://www.healthvermont.gov/BeTickSmart).\n\nContinue to take advantage of technology to play games or keep in touch with friends and family who you are not meeting up with in person. These changes will continue to be difficult, but we are all doing our part to slow down this pandemic.\n\nMost people who get sick from COVID-19 – including children – will experience mild symptoms and recover, but following the general precautions will help us limit the virus’s spread to our vulnerable populations.\n\nFind more [resources for families with children](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/communities-and-workplaces#families).",
          "date": "2020-07-24"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 4585,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4585,
          "question": "How can community helpers and volunteers keep from getting sick with COVID-19?",
          "answer": "\n\nMaking sure neighbors have what they need is crucial, but we need to make sure helpers and volunteers are still taking precautions to protect our most vulnerable Vermonters. Common sense practices can go a long way while Vermonters take care of each other.\n\nThe Vermont Department of Health recommends any volunteers bringing items to those who need to stay home:\n\n* Keep a distance of 6 feet away. \n\n* Avoid entering the person’s home. \n\n* Wear a [cloth face mask or covering](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19-VDH-mask-guidance.pdf).\n\n* Wash your hands regularly.\n\n* Avoid touching your face and cover your cough or sneeze with a tissue, then throw the tissue in the trash. \n\n* Stop doing community support work immediately if you feel sick or find out you have had contact with someone who is sick. \n\n* Keep a list of anyone you come into close contact with in case contact tracing is required. \n\n* Wear clean gloves when handling items that may be given to people with a weaker immune system, and when you are close to someone who may be sick.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 4586,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4586,
          "question": "How can I prepare at home?",
          "answer": "\n\n*   **Plan ways to care for those in your home who might be at greater risk for serious complications,** like older adults and people of any age who have underlying medical conditions. Make sure those who need regular medicine, medical supplies and equipment have what they need.\n*   **Choose a room in your home that can be used to separate sick household members from those who are healthy.** Identify a separate bathroom for the sick person to use, if possible. Plan to clean these rooms, as needed, when someone is sick.\n*   **Make sure you have enough groceries and other supplies for 14 days in case you get sick and need to quarantine.** Stock up on only what you will need for 14 days. Do not buy more than you will need so you can leave supplies for other people.\n*   **Get support from others.** Talk with your neighbors about emergency planning. If your neighborhood has Front Porch Forum, consider joining to connect with neighbors, information and resources. Stay in touch by phone or email with family and friends, especially older adults and those who have underlying medical conditions, or who live alone.\n*   **Take care of the emotional health of your household members.** Pandemics can be stressful for adults and children. Talk with your children about the pandemic, try to stay calm, and reassure them that they are safe.\n*   **Keep a daily list of other people you are in close contact with.** As the state reopens, Vermonters should consider keeping a contact journal. If you do get sick, this would make it easier to get in touch with those people and so they can take proper precautions to prevent further spread of COVID-19.\n\nThere are also [tips for large households or extended families living in the same space](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19_Prevention-Extended-Families-English.pdf).",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
