      "id": 4593,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4593,
          "question": "Can I get the virus from food?",
          "answer": "\n\nUnlike foodborne gastrointestinal (GI) viruses that often make people sick from contaminated food, COVID-19 is a virus that causes respiratory illness. The COVID-19 virus is thought to spread mainly from person-to-person. Currently, there is **no evidence to show that COVID-19 is spread through food or food packaging**.  \n\nIt is important to always follow general food safety guidelines:\n\n* Wash your hands with soap and water for 20 seconds before preparing or eating food. \n\n* Throughout the day, wash your hands after blowing your nose, coughing or sneezing, or going to the bathroom.\n\nIt may be possible that a person can get COVID-19 by touching a surface or object, like a package or container, that has the virus on it and then touching their own mouth, nose, or possibly their eyes, but this is not thought to be the main way the virus spreads.\n\nFind [shopping for food during the COVID-19 pandemic](https://www.fda.gov/food/food-safety-during-emergencies/shopping-food-during-covid-19-pandemic-information-consumers) guidance from the FDA and tips on how to [handle and prepare food safely](https://www.cdc.gov/foodsafety/) from the CDC. \n\nLearn from the CDC how to help prevent spread of the virus and [how to protect yourself and others from getting sick](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/prevention.html).",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
