    {
      "id": 4607,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4607,
          "question": "Does the Be Smart, Stay Safe Order mean I can be arrested or will need special papers if I leave my home?",
          "answer": "\n\nEnforcement of the Governor’s executive order extension — [Be Smart, Stay Safe](https://governor.vermont.gov/sites/scott/files/documents/ADDENDUM%2014%20TO%20EXECUTIVE%20ORDER%2001-20.pdf) — will be mainly be done through education and voluntary compliance.\n\n*   The Order does not close roads and does not establish roadblocks or checkpoints.\n*   Motor vehicle and pedestrian traffic will continue as Vermonters do outdoor activities that are allowed and travel to and from businesses and other entities that are open.\n*   There will not be motor vehicle stops or people detained for questioning about their travel, but law enforcement officers may be reminding people of the Order if they see groups gathering or businesses operating in violation of the Order.\n\nRead the latest updates to the [Be Smart, Stay Safe Executive Order](http://governor.vermont.gov/document-types/executive-orders)",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 4608,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4608,
          "question": "Can I use reusable grocery bags?",
          "answer": "\n\nYes, people can continue to use reusable grocery bags. However, some stores are choosing to no longer allow reusable bags and containers at this time. Check with your local store for their current policies.\n\nStores and food service establishments no longer provide plastic bags at check-out. You have the option to purchase paper bags for 10 cents each or use reusable bags. If a store has temporarily banned reusable bags, consider putting your groceries back into your cart and bag them at your car. Some stores and food establishments may still offer plastic bags after July 1 since they are allowed to use the ones they currently have in stock until they are gone.\n\nCurrent evidence suggests that the COVID-19 virus may live for hours to days on surfaces made from a variety of materials. It may be possible that a person can get COVID-19 by touching a surface or object that has the virus on it and then touching their own mouth, nose, or possibly their eyes, but this is not thought to be the main way the virus spreads. It is important to remember to wash your hands before you eat and to avoid touching your face.\n\nMake sure you clean your reusable bags regularly, which can also help prevent illnesses from bacteria, such as _E.coli_, that are from meat and unwashed fruits and vegetables.\n\nFind more information and tips about the [single-use plastics ban](https://dec.vermont.gov/content/single-use-products-law) from the Department of Environmental Conservation.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 4609,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4609,
          "question": "Is there a medicine I can take to prevent or treat COVID-19?",
          "answer": "\n\nAs reports appear in the news of certain drugs being potentially used for treatment or prevention of COVID-19, the Vermont Department of Health strongly urges caution.\n\nThough the anti-malarial drugs chloroquine and hydroxychloroquine, among others, have been widely discussed as potential treatments, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention has said there are no data currently available that shows how these drugs could be used to treat COVID-19. In fact, there are significant potential risks to taking such drugs, including death.\n\nHealth officials remind Vermonters that most people who get COVID-19 can manage their symptoms at home with rest, drinking fluids and taking fever-reducing medication. Talk to your health care provider before taking any substance alleged to prevent or treat COVID-19.\n\nProviders should only prescribe these drugs for individuals with diagnosed conditions, and not for prevention, to help maintain the supply for Vermonters who need them.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 4610,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4610,
          "question": "Where do people living with a substance use disorder go for information on treatment and recovery services?",
          "answer": "\n\nThe Vermont Department of Health has launched VTHelplink, a new, single source clearinghouse for Vermonters to receive free, confidential and personalized information and referrals to substance use prevention, treatment and recovery services throughout the state.\n\nVTHelplink features a call center of trained staff and clinicians. Callers can get information, referrals, resources and educational materials on substance use for themselves, family and friends, or on behalf of clients. \n\nThe [VTHelplink website](https://vthelplink.org/) has information resources and an [online screening tool](https://vthelplink.org/app/account/findhelp) to help Vermonters learn about treatment options that meet their needs. People can also securely chat online with call center staff through the website.\n\nThe system also includes an appointment board designed to increase accessibility of treatment appointments by tracking availability by level of service (for example, residential treatment) and population (for example, people who are pregnant). \n\n**Here’s how you can reach VTHelplink:** \n\n**Dial 802-565-LINK (5465)**. The call center is open 8:00 a.m. to 10:00 p.m. weekdays, and 8:00 a.m to 6:00 p.m. weekends and holidays, 365 days per year. \n\n**Visit [vthelplink.org](https://vthelplink.org/)**.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
