      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4615,
          "question": "Can I travel to Vermont? Are out-of-state visitors allowed?",
          "answer": "\n\nIf you are visiting or returning to Vermont you may need to quarantine for 14 days before engaging in any activities, like grocery shopping or getting together with friends or family. **Staying in and completing quarantine is extremely important to help keep people from spreading the virus when they may not know they have it.** We strongly encourage you to [sign up with Sara Alert](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/EpiInfoWebSurvey/Home/9c2e5941-1ba7-4ab4-84be-558ba7684f5d) once you arrive in Vermont to get two weeks of daily symptom check reminders. You must also follow the Governor’s [Be Smart, Stay Safe Order](https://governor.vermont.gov/covid19response).\n\nIf you are coming from [certain approved counties](https://accd.vermont.gov/covid-19/restart/cross-state-travel) with low rates of active cases, you do not need to quarantine\n\nAll other travelers coming to Vermont must quarantine.\n\nYou can either:\n\n*   Quarantine in your home state for 14 days before coming to Vermont if you are driving in your personal vehicle OR\n*   Quarantine at a lodging facility or Vermont home for 14 days if you are traveling by plane, train, bus or other means of transportation.\n\nYou have the option to get tested on Day 7 of your quarantine. Learn more under “[I am under a 14-day quarantine. Can I have the option to be tested and end my quarantine period?](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/COVID/faq/#4692)” on this page.\n\nLimit your stops when traveling to Vermont, and only stop when necessary. When you stop, follow the general precautions: wear a cloth face mask or covering, keep a 6-foot distance from others, and wash your hands often. Stay home and do not travel if you are sick.\n\nCheck the Health Department’s webpage for [what to do if you are visiting or returning to Vermont](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/traveling-vermont). Get the latest travel and quarantine guidance, learn about testing options during quarantine, and find out how to safely connect with friends and family.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 4616,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4616,
          "question": "Are lodging facilities (hotels, motels, short-term rentals, campgrounds, RV parks, or seasonal resorts) open?",
          "answer": "\n\nLodging facilities – hotels, motels, bed and breakfasts, inns, short-term rentals (for example, VRBO, Homeaway, Airbnb, etc.), and all public and private camping facilities, RV parks, seasonal resorts and marinas – may accept overnight reservations from Vermont residents and [those who have met the quarantine requirement](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/traveling-vermont). Travelers coming from [certain approved counties](https://accd.vermont.gov/covid-19/restart/cross-state-travel) with low rates of active cases do not need to quarantine.\n\nFind details and up-to-date information on [lodging, campgrounds and other accommodations](https://accd.vermont.gov/news/update-new-work-safe-additions-be-smart-stay-safe-order#lodging-campgrounds-and-other-accommodations) from the Agency of Commerce and Community and Development (ACCD) ) and find information about [traveling to Vermont](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/traveling-vermont) from the Health Department.\n\nAll guests must complete a [health questionnaire](https://accd.vermont.gov/content/pre-screening-health-survey-employees-and-visitors-entering-state-vermont-facilities) upon check-in and must provide a Vermont driver’s license or [signed document](https://accd.vermont.gov/sites/accdnew/files/documents/Lodging%20CoC%20-%20Effective%202020-06-15.pdf) certifying that they met the quarantine and travel requirements. Out-of-state guests are strongly encouraged to [sign up with Sara Alert](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/EpiInfoWebSurvey/Home/9c2e5941-1ba7-4ab4-84be-558ba7684f5d) – a free, automated and secure reminder system to check for [common symptoms of COVID-19](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/about-coronavirus-disease-covid-19) – for daily reminders from the Vermont Department of Health.\n\nIf an individual has concerns about lodging facilities that are violating the Be Smart, Stay Safe Order, the Department of Public Safety has created an online [non-compliance complaint form](http://forms.office.com/Pages/ResponsePage.aspx?id=O5O0IK26PEOcAnDtzHVZxp8VoIcMV9NNu0QyG_vdGAVUN1pLSTdOMERRR1dXOVpZMDBZUEtNVlhXMi4u) to gather more information.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        },
