      "id": 4617,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4617,
          "question": "How many people who have tested positive for COVID-19 are in my town or county?",
          "answer": "\n\nYou can find the number of people who have tested positive for COVID-19 by county on the [Current Activity in Vermont data dashboard](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/current-activity-vermont). This map is updated daily.\n\nBelow the data dashboard, there is a map showing the number of Vermonters who have tested positive for COVID-19 by the town where they live. Residents of long-term care facilities and inmates at correctional facilities are included in the town of their facility when they were tested. This map is updated weekly.\n\nWhen looking at the county numbers, please remember that low or no recent cases is not the same as “safer.” We know the virus is in our communities, and we should continue to follow health guidance to slow the spread of COVID-19 – no matter what county we live in or visit. The map reflects the number of people who had a positive test. There may be active cases in your county that haven’t been tested. \n\nA [Weekly Summary of Vermont COVID-19 Data](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/Weekly-Summary-of-Data.pdf) is also available that includes more details on who has been impacted by COVID-19 in Vermont. You can find out more about testing trends, outbreaks, pre-existing conditions and symptoms of Vermonters with COVID-19.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 4618,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4618,
          "question": "What is isolation, quarantine and self-observation?",
          "answer": "\n\n**Isolation** is for people who are sick with COVID-19.\n\n**Quarantine** is for people with no symptoms who are returning to Vermont from certain out-of-state locations or people who were in close contact with someone sick with COVID-19. Quarantine helps prevent spread of disease before a person knows they are sick or if they are infected with the virus and don’t have symptoms.\n\nQuarantine means staying at a home or dwelling for 14 days before doing any activities outside of the home, like grocery shopping or getting together with friends or family. People in quarantine should separate themselves from others and check themselves for symptoms. We strongly encourage anyone with symptoms to sign up for [daily symptom check reminders](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/EpiInfoWebSurvey/Home/9c2e5941-1ba7-4ab4-84be-558ba7684f5d).\n\n**Self-observation** is for other Vermonters who don’t have symptoms of COVID-19.\n\nLearn more about  [isolation, quarantine and self-observation](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19-chart-observation-isolation-quarantine_final.pdf).\n\nCheck the [latest quarantine guidance](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/traveling-vermont) for people visiting or returning to Vermont.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 4619,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4619,
          "question": "Can I volunteer to help with the State’s response to COVID-19?",
          "answer": "\n\nYes, people with medical and health care skills and those with other needed skills can sign up for volunteer assistance to support the State’s response to COVID-19. We currently have a contact tracing team in place, but these are other ways you can help.\n\nPeople with medical or other health care backgrounds are needed to support the health care providers responding to the COVID-19 pandemic. Vermont’s Medical Reserve Corps units are community-based groups of volunteers who supplement local emergency and public health resources with their existing skills.\n\nSign up with the [Vermont Medical Reserve Corps](https://www.vermont.gov/volunteer) if you:\n\n*   Are a licensed and certified health care professional\n*   Have health, mental health, or other types of clinical or professional experience\n*   Have health care administrative experience, such as with medical data entry or language translators\n*   Have worked with displaced individuals, such as homeless shelter programs\n\nVermont has eased licensing requirements for the purposes of aiding this emergency response. Physicians, physician assistants and podiatrists can learn more on the [Board of Medical Practice website](https://www.healthvermont.gov/health-professionals-systems/board-medical-practice/COVID19). Other medical professionals, including nurses and osteopathic physicians, can learn more on the [Office of Professional Regulation's website](https://sos.vermont.gov/opr/about-opr/covid-19-response/).\n\n**Other individuals who have needed skills** (for example, drivers, food service, construction, IT, security, skilled trades, etc.), can sign up at [vermont.gov/volunteer](https://www.vermont.gov/volunteer) and indicate their expertise and availability.\n\nVermonters can also: \n\n*   Donate blood with the [American Red Cross](https://www.redcross.org/local/new-hampshire-vermont.html).\n*   Support your [local Food Bank by donating online](https://www.vtfoodbank.org/) or you can text GIVEHEALTH to 85511. The [Vermont Foodbank can help](https://www.vtfoodbank.org/) if you need it.\n*   Donate or volunteer with community organizations or emergency supply efforts.\n*   Help your neighbors – older adults and people of any age who have underlying medical conditions should stay close to home as much as possible. Go shopping for a neighbor or someone else in need, keep an older neighbor company by phone or at a safe distance. \n\nWhen volunteering please follow the [guidelines on being a good neighbor](https://vem.vermont.gov/neighborly).",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
