        {
          "id": 4635,
          "question": "I split custody with my children. Can we still continue to bring our children from one home to another, or do we need to follow the 14-day self-quarantine for each visit?",
          "answer": "\n\nThe Health Department encourages parents to follow State and CDC guidelines for travel and social distancing. Be sure to consider the health of each household, including if anyone in the homes has current symptoms of COVID-19 or has an underlying medical condition before moving a child between them. Learn how to [safely connect with friends and family](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/Safely_Connect_with_Friends_and_Family_FINAL.pdf).\n\nIf one of the parents has concerns and does not want to move children between households, we encourage parents to consult with their child’s pediatrician to discuss any possible health risks to the child.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 4637,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4637,
          "question": "Does the Be Smart, Stay Safe Order ban travel to neighboring states for work or court-ordered parental visitation?",
          "answer": "\n\nNo. If you work in a neighboring state, or if you need to drop off or pick up children from court-ordered parental visits, for example, that is considered essential travel, and you do not need to quarantine.\n\nHowever, if you come in close contact with someone sick with COVID-19, you should self-quarantine for 14 days, no matter where the contact occurred.\n\nLearn more about [what to do if you’re a close contact of someone with COVID-19](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19_What-to-do-if-you-are-a-close-contact-of-someone-with-COVID-19_final.pdf).\n\nAnyone currently under quarantine who has had no symptoms during the first seven days of quarantine has the option to be tested with a PCR test. Find out how under [“I am under a 14-day quarantine. Can I have the option to be tested and end my quarantine period?”](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/COVID/faq/#4692) on this page.\n\nFind out more about [traveling to Vermont](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/traveling-vermont).",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        },
        {
          "id": 4637,
          "question": "Do I need to quarantine if I work in a neighboring state or have parental shared custody?",
          "answer": "\n\nNo. If you live near a border and regularly travel to and from a neighboring state, you may make day trips to that state for work, health care, and other essential needs like groceries or visitation for parental shared custody, without quarantining.\n\nHowever, if you come in close contact with someone sick with COVID-19, you should self-quarantine for 14 days, no matter where the contact occurred. Learn more about [what to do if you’re a close contact of someone with COVID-19](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19_What-to-do-if-you-are-a-close-contact-of-someone-with-COVID-19_final.pdf).\n\nIf you travel out of state for another reason and to a location that is **not** in an [approved county with low rates of active cases](https://accd.vermont.gov/covid-19/restart/cross-state-travel), you must quarantine for 14 days in Vermont upon return. This includes day trips. Find up-to-date information about [travel and COVID-19](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/traveling-vermont).\n\nAnyone currently under quarantine who has had no symptoms during the first seven days of quarantine has the option to be tested with a PCR test. Find out how under [“I am under a 14-day quarantine. Can I have the option to be tested and end my quarantine period?”](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/COVID/faq/#4692) on this page.",
          "date": "2020-07-24"
        }
      ]
    },
