      "id": 4639,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4639,
          "question": "How is Vermont deciding when it is safe to reopen?",
          "answer": "\n\nMost recent modeling data suggests Vermont has reached its peak in the number of new cases of COVID-19, hospital capacity, and the number people who are currently infected with COVID-19.\n\nHowever, it is important to remember that not everyone infected with the virus has symptoms and there are still many people who are currently infected and could spread it to others.\n\nVermont is looking at four key measures to inform steps to reopen:\n\n*   Ongoing reduction in cases for at least 14 days\n*   A health care system that is safely able to treat all patients without exceeding its capacity or using crisis standards of care\n*   The ability to test all people with symptoms\n*   Widespread active monitoring of people who have tested positive for COVID-19 and tracing their close contacts\n\nAt this time, Vermont continues to do well in keeping the number of cases of COVID-19 down. This is hopeful news. To continue on this path, it is critical that Vermonters continue to follow the general precautions to keep the virus from spreading and to help save lives: wear a cloth face mask or covering, keep a 6-foot distance from others, wash your hands often, and stay home if you are sick. \n\nRead the latest [Vermont COVID-19 modeling projections](https://dfr.vermont.gov/about-us/covid-19/modeling) from the Vermont Department of Financial Regulation.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
