          "id": 4643,
          "question": "Where can I get tested for COVID-19?",
          "answer": "\n\nIf you are having [symptoms of COVID-19](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/about-coronavirus-disease-covid-19), call your health care provider for a referral. If you do not have a health care provider, call 2-1-1 to be connected with a local [community or hospital-connected clinic](https://www.navigateresources.net/211vermont/Subcategory.aspx?;;0;;N;0;276976;Health%20Care,%20Dental%20Care) for a referral to a test site. If you are having a medical emergency, call 9-1-1 or go to the hospital.\n\nFind out [what to do if you are sick](https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/if-you-are-sick/index.html) from the CDC and [what to do while you’re waiting for test results](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/HS-ID-COVID19-Waiting-For-Test-Results-Handout.pdf).\n\n**Pop-up Testing Sites and Pharmacy Testing Locations**\n\nAny person without symptoms who lives or works in Vermont can be tested at no cost at a pop-up testing site without a doctor’s referral. This includes people who live in a neighboring state and work in Vermont, second homeowners, and college students. Children under 12 months cannot be tested at a pop-up testing site. Please talk to your child’s doctor about testing options.\n\n[Register to guarantee your spot](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/testing-covid-19). People who do not have internet access and want to register at a pop-up testing site can call 2-1-1 for help with registration. For pop-up testing site registration questions and issues, call 802-828-2828. If you need transportation to a pop-up testing site, please call 833-387-7200 at least two days before your scheduled appointment.\n\nYou will get a call from the Health Department when your results are ready, which is usually within 2 to 4 days, if not sooner. You will also get a letter in the mail within 7 days of being tested.\n\nThe test is a nasopharyngeal swab, or NP swab, where a health care provider uses a long swab to collect a sample from the back of the nose and throat. A limited supply of nasal swabs may be available for children or other priority groups, where a health care provider uses a short swab to collect a sample from the front of the nose. These are known as PCR tests will tell you if you have a current infection. They are not a serology/antibody test, which means the test will not tell you if you were infected in the past.\n\nSome pharmacies may offer testing at no cost for people without symptoms. Call the pharmacy first to see if testing is offered and to schedule an appointment.\n\nFind more information about [testing and testing locations](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/testing-covid-19).\n\nSome commercial businesses may offer other testing opportunities. You can contact them directly for more information.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        },
