        {
          "id": 4652,
          "question": "I have recovered from COVID-19. Can I donate my blood plasma to help other people suffering from COVID-19?",
          "answer": "\n\nPeople who have fully recovered from COVID-19 have antibodies in their blood plasma. This is the body’s immune response to the virus. Currently, plasma donations are only being done experimentally. It has not yet been confirmed by the scientific community. However, it could prove to be important in the future to treating serious cases of illness from COVID-19.\n\nThe Red Cross is looking for people who are fully recovered from COVID-19 and may be able to donate plasma. If you are fully recovered from a COVID-19 diagnosis that was confirmed by a lab test and would like to donate your plasma, [fill out the form on the Red Cross website](https://www.redcrossblood.org/donate-blood/dlp/plasma-donations-from-recovered-covid-19-patients.html).",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 4653,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4653,
          "question": "Is there universal (widespread) testing being done at group living facilities?",
          "answer": "\n\nVermont is taking additional measures to slow the spread of COVID-19 in certain types of group living facilities. This includes nursing homes, corrections facilities, residential homes for people with disabilities, residential treatment centers, assisted living facilities, state psychiatric care facilities, and homeless shelters. If a staff member or resident tests positive for COVID-19, universal testing of all staff and residents is offered at these facilities. Staff and residents may decline testing, and facilities may decline universal testing.\n\nAdditionally, when a person tests positive at a skilled nursing facility, sequential testing is offered to those who tested negative during the universal testing.\n\nAny new admissions to nursing homes, assisted living residences, and residential care homes must complete the full 14-day quarantine period first.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
