          "id": 4674,
          "question": "What do I do if I'm a close contact of someone who is waiting for their test results?",
          "answer": "\n\nPeople can be contagious for up to 48 hours before showing symptoms, so you should quarantine for 48 hours or until the test results come back.\n\nIf the test results come back positive (the person has COVID-19), then you should continue to quarantine for 14 days. Anyone currently under quarantine who has had no symptoms during the first seven days of quarantine has the option to be tested with a PCR test. Find out how under [“I am under a 14-day quarantine. Can I have the option to be tested and end my quarantine period?”](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/COVID/faq/#4692) on this page.\n\nIf the test results come back negative (the person does not have COVID-19), then you should start self-observation.\n\nRead the [What is isolation, quarantine and self-observation?](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/COVID-19-chart-observation-isolation-quarantine_final.pdf) chart for details.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
