          "id": 4683,
          "question": "Who is getting tested for COVID-19 in Vermont?",
          "answer": "\n\nIf you are having [symptoms of COVID-19](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/about-coronavirus-disease-covid-19), call your health care provider to be tested. If you do not have a health care provider, call 2-1-1 to be connected with a local [community or hospital-connected clinic](https://www.navigateresources.net/211vermont/Subcategory.aspx?;;0;;N;0;276976;Health%20Care,%20Dental%20Care) for referral to a test site.\n\nHealth care providers are encouraged to order a test for any child or adult who is showing symptoms of COVID-19, even if their symptoms are mild.\n\nSince late April, we have been able to conduct about 1,000 tests a day – or 7,000 tests a week. With more testing we are likely to see a rise in positive cases, and we are prepared to handle such a scenario. A Testing and Tracing Task Force was created to guide and oversee this process.\n\nTesting is currently available for:\n\n*   Any adult or child with symptoms of COVID-19 – even if their symptoms are mild – who has been referred for testing by their doctor.\n*   Long-term care facilities and other group living settings:\n    *   All residents and staff in group living settings, where there has been a single positive test. This includes nursing homes, assisted living facilities, prisons, and certain high-density residential buildings.\n    *   If there is a person who has tested positive with COVID-19 at a skilled nursing facility, they can be retested at 3 days, 7 days, 10 days and 14 days after the initial test. This is to help prevent community-wide outbreaks.\n    *   For all sites, regardless of whether a person has tested positive, testing is offered at intake, discharge, and for certain residents who require regular care outside of the facility.\n*   Staff at correctional facilities\n*   Any Vermonter without symptoms can be tested at a [pop-up testing site](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/resources#testing) without a doctor’s referral, but registration for testing is required. Regular test collection locations still require a doctor’s referral.\n*   Anyone currently under quarantine who has had no symptoms during the first seven days of quarantine can be tested with a PCR test. Find out how under [“I am under a 14-day quarantine. Can I have the option to be tested and end my quarantine period?”](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/COVID/faq/#4692) on this page.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        },
