    {
      "id": 4690,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4690,
          "question": "Can I get together with friends and family?",
          "answer": "\n\nVermonters can get together with friends and family. There are no group size limits to social gatherings and parties that are not held at [event venues](https://accd.vermont.gov/news/update-new-work-safe-additions-stay-home-stay-safe-order#event-venues). However, we recommend keeping groups small whenever possible to limit any possible exposure to the virus, and following these general precautions: wearing a cloth face mask or covering, keeping a 6-foot distance from others, washing your hands often, and staying home if you are sick. Learn more about how to [safely connect with friends and family](https://www.healthvermont.gov/sites/default/files/documents/pdf/Safely_Connect_with_Friends_and_Family_FINAL.pdf).\n\nChoose other trusted households that are also taking health and safety precautions. A trusted household is one that has taken seriously the importance of following the general precautions in their day-to-day lives.\n\nConsider keeping a contact journal – a list of other people who you have been in close contact with each day. If you do get sick, this would make it easier to get in touch with those people and so they can take proper precautions to prevent further spread of the virus.\n\nTo keep COVID-19 from spreading, we must continue to:\n\n*   Wear a cloth face mask or covering over your nose and mouth.\n*   Stay home and away from others if you are sick or have recently been exposed to someone who has COVID-19.\n*   Keep a 6-foot distance from others who are not part of your household.\n*   Wash your hands frequently (use hand sanitizer with at least 60% alcohol when soap and water are not available).\n*   Cough and sneeze into your elbow (even if you are wearing a cloth face mask or covering).\n*   Limit travel to within Vermont, or to [places that have been identified as low risk](https://accd.vermont.gov/covid-19/restart/cross-state-travel), as much as possible and limit non-essential stops when you do travel.\n\nThe risk for severe illness increases with age and is higher for older adults and people of any age with certain underlying medical conditions. They should stay close to home, and family and friends should do everything they can to help keep them safe.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
