      "id": 4692,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4692,
          "question": "I am under a 14-day quarantine. Can I have the option to be tested and end my quarantine period?",
          "answer": "\n\nAnyone currently under quarantine who has had no symptoms during the first seven days of quarantine has the option to be tested. The test must be a PCR test. Talk to your health care provider to find out where to get tested. If you do not have a health care provider, call 2-1-1. For travelers who are [completing quarantine in their home state](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/traveling-vermont), your home state may offer testing for people without symptoms.\n\n**You can end your quarantine period before 14 days only if**:\n\n*   You have not had [symptoms](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/about-coronavirus-disease-covid-19) during your quarantine period;\n*   You are tested on Day 7 or later;\n*   You remain in quarantine until the result comes back; AND\n*   You receive a negative test result and are still not having symptoms.\n\nFor anyone coming into Vermont, Day 1 is the day after you arrive in Vermont.\n\nHowever, if you end your quarantine period before 14 days, you must continue to monitor yourself for symptoms for the full 14 days. If you develop symptoms at any point during your quarantine, contact your health care provider and the Health Department right away. If you do not have a health care provider, call 2-1-1. [Sign up to receive daily symptom check reminders](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/EpiInfoWebSurvey/Home/9c2e5941-1ba7-4ab4-84be-558ba7684f5d).\n\nFor **close contacts** of people who have tested positive:\n\n*   **If you are NOT able to completely physically separate yourself** from the person who tested positive – for example, you live in the same home – Day 1 of your quarantine is the day after they have ended their self-isolation.\n*   **If you are able to completely physically separate** from the person who tested positive – for example you do not live in the same home – Day 1 of your quarantine is the day after the last time you were in close contact with them.\n\nStudies have found most people will develop symptoms by Day 7. This why there is the option for people to be tested at Day 7 or after in their quarantine and, if the test is negative, to end quarantine.\n\nNew admissions to nursing homes, assisted living residences, and residential care homes must complete the full 14-day quarantine.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 4693,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4693,
          "question": "Can I get COVID-19 from swimming in a lake or river?",
          "answer": "\n\nThe COVID-19 virus could possibly enter waterways through untreated wastewater that is discharged into waterways following large rain events or for other reasons. The virus has been found in untreated wastewater, but there has been no evidence that a person can get COVID-19 from being exposed to untreated wastewater or sewerage systems.\n\nAccording to the CDC, it is thought that the COVID-19 virus does not spread through standard municipal and individual septic system wastewater treatment practices. Guidance will be updated if anything new is learned.\n\nThe Health Department recommends that towns do routine weekly _E. coli_ testing and after large storm events during the swim season. These tests are a good indication of the water quality, meaning that if the _E. coli_ levels are low, then COVID-19 virus levels are also expected to be low.\n\nThe best practices for staying healthy while swimming are to obey signage at beaches, do not swim during and following large rain events, and do not swallow the water.\n\nWhen you are at a beach or swimming spot, be sure to follow the general precautions to prevent the spread of the virus — wear a cloth face mask or covering when you’re not in the water, keep a 6-foot distance from others, wash your hands often, and stay home if you are sick. Plan to “arrive, play, and leave” — avoiding gathering before and after activities and giving others space.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
