      "id": 4700,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4700,
          "question": "Why is Vermont testing people who do not have symptoms of COVID-19?",
          "answer": "\n\nThe CDC issued a recommendation that testing should be occurring at a particular rate per 100,000 people. This is so we can see if the case numbers start to grow again as the state reopens. In Vermont, to achieve that rate, we need to test about 1,000 people per day.\n\nTesting helps us better understand the current rate of active infections of COVID-19 in Vermont, and helps to contain and slow the spread to others. It also lets us see how that rate is changing over time as we continue to reopen the state.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 4701,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4701,
          "question": "What should returning and new college students do?",
          "answer": "\n\nCheck the Health Department’s webpage for [what to do if you are visiting or returning to Vermont](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/traveling-vermont). Get the latest travel and quarantine guidance, learn about testing options during quarantine, and find out how to safely connect with friends and family.\n\nStudents from [certain approved counties](https://accd.vermont.gov/covid-19/restart/cross-state-travel) with low rates of active cases do not need to quarantine.\n\nAll students are strongly encouraged to [sign up with Sara Alert](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/EpiInfoWebSurvey/Home/9c2e5941-1ba7-4ab4-84be-558ba7684f5d) once arriving in Vermont to get two weeks of daily symptom check reminders.\n\nCollege students returning to Burlington can also use the city’s [Supportive Quarantine Pilot Program](https://www.burlingtonvt.gov/covid-19/quarantine). The program includes a move-in care package of fresh local goods, a mask, and hygiene supplies.\n\nColleges and universities must follow the [Mandatory Guidance for College and University Campus Learning](https://accd.vermont.gov/content/restart-plan-college-and-university-campus-learning). For specific questions about what you need to do, please contact your college or university.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 4702,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4702,
          "question": "Can I get tested with a swab in the front of my nose?",
          "answer": "\n\nThere is a test available that uses a dry swab to collect a sample from the front of your nose, called a nasal swab. At this time, the supplies needed for this type of test are limited. This type of test is being prioritized for different groups of people who may not be able to tolerate the longer swab that collects samples from the back of the nose and throat, called a nasopharyngeal or NP swab. This includes children, patients at risk of increased bleeding or complications, patients with nasal irregularities (for example, polyps, deviated septum), people who need regular and repeated testing (for example, employees or residents of skilled nursing facilities), and those without the cognitive ability to understand the testing procedure.\n\nYour health care provider will determine if you should be referred for a nasal swab. Please note the pop-up testing sites use the longer NP swabs, but may have a limited supply of the shorter nasal swabs available for the groups of people listed above.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 4703,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4703,
          "question": "What is Sara Alert?",
          "answer": "\n\nSara Alert is a free, automated and secure reminder system to check for [common symptoms of COVID-19](https://www.healthvermont.gov/response/coronavirus-covid-19/about-coronavirus-disease-covid-19). People who have tested positive for COVID-19, their close contacts, and people traveling or returning to Vermont can quickly and easily sign up for to receive free daily reminders to check themselves for symptoms by email, text or phone call. If symptoms are reported, the Health Department will reach out to provide guidance and next steps. Sara Alert helps our public health teams contain the spread of COVID-19.\n\nPlease note, Sara Alert is not a contact tracing system. It is not GPS based, so it does not monitor your movements.\n\nIf you are traveling or returning to Vermont, you are strongly encouraged to sign up with Sara Alert once you arrive in Vermont to get two weeks of daily symptom check reminders.\n\n[Sign up for Sara Alert](https://apps.health.vermont.gov/EpiInfoWebSurvey/Home/9c2e5941-1ba7-4ab4-84be-558ba7684f5d).",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
