      "id": 4706,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4706,
          "question": "Why is the Health Department measuring blood oxygen levels in people who test positive for COVID-19?",
          "answer": "\n\nPeople diagnosed COVID-19 may have below-normal levels of oxygen in their blood before they feel short of breath. Finding low oxygen levels early helps people know to seek medical care sooner. This could make the disease less severe.\n\nThe Health Department has a new program that gives people who have tested positive for COVID-19 a free pulse oximeter to use at home. A pulse oximeter is a small device that clips onto your fingertip to measure your pulse and the oxygen levels in your body.\n\nA Health Department staff member will contact the person who has tested positive for COVID-19 within about 24 hours. They will ask questions about their symptoms and if they have a pulse oximeter at home. If they do not have one, they will receive one within one to two days. They will then be asked to use it to monitor their oxygen levels throughout the day. The Health Department will continue to regularly contact them over the next couple of days to ask what their oxygen levels were and about any symptoms they may have.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": 4707,
      "revisions": [
        {
          "id": 4707,
          "question": "What can I wear if my health or work environment doesn't allow me to wear a cloth face mask or covering?",
          "answer": "\n\nPeople who have trouble breathing can wear a light-weight bandanna or cloth covering tied to be open at the bottom or a face shield. Face shields are generally not recommended because they are more for health care settings to protect the person wearing it from droplets getting into their eyes. Face masks or coverings, like a cloth face mask or bandanna, do a better job than face shields of keeping droplets in. However, if your work environment or health does not allow you to wear a cloth face mask, wearing a face shield is better than having no barrier on your nose and mouth.\n\nOutdoor workers who are doing strenuous work that causes heavy breathing are not required to wear a cloth face mask or covering when it is hot outside. Workers should keep masks with them and wear them when they are not exerting themselves (for example talking, resting, or interacting with other co-workers or people). It is important that workers keep a 6-foot distance from others whenever possible, especially when they are not wearing a mask.",
          "date": "2020-07-21"
        },
